I&#39;m not entirely sure _why_ you would want to store Post Meta into a separate table, but I&#39;ve had situations where I&#39;ve needed to do crazier things.

The gist would be that you can use your [Custom Meta Box](https://developer.wordpress.org/plugins/metadata/custom-meta-boxes/) to display the form fields, and then handle those form fields with your own custom function on the [`save_post`](https://codex.wordpress.org/Plugin_API/Action_Reference/save_post) hook.

Let&#39;s say you&#39;ve registered a custom meta box with `&lt;input name=&quot;my_custom_table_field&quot; /&gt;` in it. Instead of using [`update_post_meta()`](https://codex.wordpress.org/Function_Reference/update_post_meta) on the `save_post` hooks, you could write a function that manages the data with the [`$wpdb-&gt;update`](https://developer.wordpress.org/reference/classes/wpdb/update/) method. Something like this would get you started:

	add_action( &#39;save_post&#39;, &#39;save_my_custom_data&#39; );
	function save_my_custom_data( $post_id ){
		global $wpdb;

		if( isset( $_POST[&#39;my_custom_table_field&#39;] ){
			$result = $wpdb-&gt;update(
				&#39;my_custom_table&#39;,
				array(
					&#39;post_id&#39; =&gt; $post_id,
